--- body ---
## Context

The orchestrator's Phase 7 (scope audit) says "split out-of-scope work to new
tickets (`/new-ticket`)" but gives no guidance on what happens to the commits.
By Phase 7 the work is already done and committed on the PR branch.

The skill is currently ambiguous between:
- A: Create a ticket for the extra work; leave commits in the PR; human aware.
- B: `git rebase -i` to excise out-of-scope commits into a separate PR.

Option B is risky and unsuitable for autonomous agents (destructive git ops,
conflict risk, test coverage across the split). Option A is the default.

Exception: if the out-of-scope commits form a clean orthogonal set (separate
files, no interleaving with in-scope changes), the agent *may* escalate to the
human with a proposed split rather than auto-accepting the creep — but this is
a human decision, not an autonomous one.

## Actions

1. Update `skills/orchestrator/SKILL.md` Phase 7 to state the policy explicitly:

   > **Default:** create a new ticket (via `/new-ticket`) for the out-of-scope
   > work. Leave the commits in the PR. Note the new ticket ID in the PR body
   > under "Scope note". Do not rewrite git history.
   >
   > **Exception:** if the out-of-scope commits are orthogonal (no shared files,
   > no interleaved hunks with in-scope changes), escalate with a proposed split
   > and the relevant commit SHAs. The human decides.
   >
   > **Never** rebase or amend autonomously to excise scope creep.

2. Add an ESCALATE path for Phase 7 alongside the existing REROLL/APPROVED paths
   in the orchestrator wrap-up, so creep that can't be cleanly ticketed stops the
   run rather than silently including unticketed work.

## Test

No automated test — this is a skill/doc change. Verify by reading the updated
Phase 7 section and confirming it matches the policy above.

## Exit criteria

- Phase 7 section of `orchestrator/SKILL.md` contains an explicit "Default /
  Exception / Never" policy on commit handling.
- The skill references `/new-ticket` and specifies where the new ticket ID is
  recorded (PR body "Scope note").
- An ESCALATE path is described for cases where ticketing the creep is not enough.
